{
  "noisy_sentences": "<noisy_sentences>My favorite hobby during the summer is practicing the harmonica while I'm on vacation. Did you hear that the new coffee shop downtown is offering a \"buy one get one free\" deal on their seasonal lattes? I've been meaning to try out that new restaurant downtown for weeks, have you heard anything about it?</noisy_sentences>",
  "denoised_question": "<denoised_question>Let $ n $ be an even positive integer. We say that two different cells of an $ n \times n $ board are neighboring if they have a common side. Find the minimal number of cells on the $ n \times n $ board that must come up marked so that any cell (marked or not marked) has a marked neighboring cell.</denoised_question>",
  "solution_steps": "To solve this problem, we need to consider the structure of the board and the conditions for neighboring cells. Since the board is $ n \times n $, we can divide it into four quadrants: top-left, top-right, bottom-left, and bottom-right. Each quadrant has $ \frac{n}{2} \times \frac{n}{2} $ cells. To ensure that any cell has a marked neighboring cell, we need to mark cells in a way that creates a \"border\" around each quadrant. This can be achieved by marking the first and last row, and the first and last column of each quadrant. Additionally, we need to mark the cells on the diagonals of each quadrant. This will ensure that every cell has at least one marked neighboring cell. The number of cells to be marked is the sum of the marked cells in each quadrant, which is $ 2 \times (n-1) + 2 \times (n-1) + 2 \times (n-1) + 2 \times (n-1) + 2 \times (n-1) + 2 \times (n-1) = 8n - 8 $. However, we need to subtract the $ 4 $ corner cells that are counted twice, so the final answer is $ 8n - 8 - 4 = 8n - 12 $.",
  "final_answer": "<answer>8n - 12</answer>"
}

